{"type":"message","id":"37f30d9a","parentId":"c0f413e5","timestamp":"2026-03-19T04:01:40.491Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Considering extraction methods**\n\nI’m thinking about how to extract data without using Beautiful Soup 4 (bs4). It seems like I might need to rely on regular expressions (regex) instead. I wonder how effective regex would be for this task. I’ll need to consider the complexities of the data and whether regex can handle it well. This could definitely streamline the process, but I want to ensure I’m capturing the necessary information accurately. Let's explore this further!\n\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_Kd58XEQxmwDOuF3m7JFfyke3","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 - <<'PY'\nimport requests,re,json,html\nurl='https://coinmarketcap.com/academy/article/what-is-openclaw-moltbot-clawdbot-ai-agent-crypto-twitter'\ntext=requests.get(url,timeout=20,headers={'User-Agent':'Mozilla/5.0'}).text\nprint('len',len(text))\nfor pat in ['__NEXT_DATA__','application/ld+json','articleBody','OpenClaw','MoltBot','Clawdbot']:\n    print(pat, text.find(pat))\nmt=re.search(r'<title>(.*?)</title>',text,re.S)\nprint('TITLE:', html.unescape(mt.group(1)) if mt else 'none')\n# dump snippets around likely article body markers\nfor pat in ['articleBody','\"content\"','\"body\"','\"article\"']:\n    idx=text.find(pat)\n    if idx!=-1:\n        print('\\nPAT',pat,'IDX',idx)\n        print(text[idx:idx+1200])\n        break\nPY","workdir":"/home/zbb/.openclaw/workspace","yieldMs":20000,"timeout":40}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":1268,"output":300,"cacheRead":32256,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":33824,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773892891559}}
{"type":"message","id":"d5539a06","parentId":"37f30d9a","timestamp":"2026-03-19T04:01:46.004Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_Kd58XEQxmwDOuF3m7JFfyke3","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"len 215285\n__NEXT_DATA__ 119974\napplication/ld+json 4887\narticleBody -1\nOpenClaw 3728\nMoltBot 4051\nClawdbot 4063\nTITLE: What is OpenClaw? The AI Agent Assistant Lighting Up Crypto Twitter | CoinMarketCap\n\nPAT \"content\" IDX 120591\n\"content\":\"\\u003cp\\u003eIn the fast-moving world of artificial intelligence, a week is a long time. For OpenClaw (formerly Clawdbot and then MoltBot), the last seven days have been a masterclass in viral growth, but trademark disputes and a stream of mishaps have marred its potential.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eWhat started as a niche tool for developers has turned into a cautionary tale of \\\"The Great Molt\\\" — a rebrand that saw millions of dollars vanish in minutes while simultaneously cementing OpenClaw as a potential game-changer for crypto degens.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003ch2 id=\\\"what-is-openclaw\\\"\\u003eWhat is OpenClaw?\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eOpenClaw is a self-hosted \\u003ca href=\\\"https://coinmarketcap.com/academy/glossary/ai-agents\\\" rel=\\\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\\\"\\u003eAI agent\\u003c/a\\u003e assistant created by developer Peter Steinberger. Unlike a standard chatbot, OpenClaw is designed to live on your local hardware — often a Mac Mini — and execute real-world tasks.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eIt can:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cul\\u003e\\u003cli\\u003eControl your browser\\u003c/li\\u003e\\u003cli\\u003eRun terminal commands\\u003c/li\\u003e\\u003cli\\u003ePlan and execute tasks autonomo"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":5505,"aggregated":"len 215285\n__NEXT_DATA__ 119974\napplication/ld+json 4887\narticleBody -1\nOpenClaw 3728\nMoltBot 4051\nClawdbot 4063\nTITLE: What is OpenClaw? The AI Agent Assistant Lighting Up Crypto Twitter | CoinMarketCap\n\nPAT \"content\" IDX 120591\n\"content\":\"\\u003cp\\u003eIn the fast-moving world of artificial intelligence, a week is a long time. For OpenClaw (formerly Clawdbot and then MoltBot), the last seven days have been a masterclass in viral growth, but trademark disputes and a stream of mishaps have marred its potential.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eWhat started as a niche tool for developers has turned into a cautionary tale of \\\"The Great Molt\\\" — a rebrand that saw millions of dollars vanish in minutes while simultaneously cementing OpenClaw as a potential game-changer for crypto degens.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003ch2 id=\\\"what-is-openclaw\\\"\\u003eWhat is OpenClaw?\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eOpenClaw is a self-hosted \\u003ca href=\\\"https://coinmarketcap.com/academy/glossary/ai-agents\\\" rel=\\\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\\\"\\u003eAI agent\\u003c/a\\u003e assistant created by developer Peter Steinberger. Unlike a standard chatbot, OpenClaw is designed to live on your local hardware — often a Mac Mini — and execute real-world tasks.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eIt can:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cul\\u003e\\u003cli\\u003eControl your browser\\u003c/li\\u003e\\u003cli\\u003eRun terminal commands\\u003c/li\\u003e\\u003cli\\u003ePlan and execute tasks autonomo","cwd":"/home/zbb/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773892906001}}
{"type":"message","id":"75893ace","parentId":"d5539a06","timestamp":"2026-03-19T04:01:55.274Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Extracting content**\n\nI want to extract the content I need, and I'm considering using regex to decode the JSON string closely related to that content. It sounds like a straightforward task, but I should be careful to ensure that the regex patterns I’m using correctly match the structure of the JSON. I also need to verify that I'm extracting the right parts. Let's dive into this and get it right!\n\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_M3H7cNF1TBrIUEo1zmIkHAA3","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 - <<'PY'\nimport requests,re,json,html\nurl='https://coinmarketcap.com/academy/article/what-is-openclaw-moltbot-clawdbot-ai-agent-crypto-twitter'\ntext=requests.get(url,timeout=20,headers={'User-Agent':'Mozilla/5.0'}).text\n# Extract __NEXT_DATA__ json\nm=re.search(r'<script id=\"__NEXT_DATA__\" type=\"application/json\">(.*?)</script>', text)\nassert m, 'no next data'\ndata=json.loads(html.unescape(m.group(1)))\n# recursively find content/title\nfound=[]\n\ndef walk(obj,path='root'):\n    if isinstance(obj,dict):\n        if 'content' in obj and isinstance(obj['content'],str) and ('OpenClaw' in obj['content'] or 'MoltBot' in obj['content']):\n            found.append((path,obj))\n        for k,v in obj.items():\n            walk(v,f'{path}.{k}')\n    elif isinstance(obj,list):\n        for i,v in enumerate(obj):\n            walk(v,f'{path}[{i}]')\nwalk(data)\nprint('found',len(found))\nfor path,obj in found[:3]:\n    print('PATH',path)\n    print('keys',obj.keys())\n    print('title',obj.get('title'))\n    print('content snippet',obj['content'][:2000])\nPY","workdir":"/home/zbb/.openclaw/workspace","yieldMs":20000,"timeout":40}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":34222,"output":399,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":34621,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773892906005}}
{"type":"message","id":"1adc8e68","parentId":"75893ace","timestamp":"2026-03-19T04:02:00.784Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_M3H7cNF1TBrIUEo1zmIkHAA3","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"found 1\nPATH root.props.pageProps.article\nkeys dict_keys(['id', 'title', 'slug', 'meta', 'visible', 'image', 'content', 'disclaimer', 'language', 'created_at', 'updated_at', 'reading_time', 'likes', 'shares', 'srd', 'related', 'available_languages', 'difficulty', 'categories', 'author', 'assets'])\ntitle What is OpenClaw? The AI Agent Assistant Lighting Up Crypto Twitter\ncontent snippet <p>In the fast-moving world of artificial intelligence, a week is a long time. For OpenClaw (formerly Clawdbot and then MoltBot), the last seven days have been a masterclass in viral growth, but trademark disputes and a stream of mishaps have marred its potential.</p><p>What started as a niche tool for developers has turned into a cautionary tale of \"The Great Molt\" — a rebrand that saw millions of dollars vanish in minutes while simultaneously cementing OpenClaw as a potential game-changer for crypto degens.</p><h2 id=\"what-is-openclaw\">What is OpenClaw?</h2><p>OpenClaw is a self-hosted <a href=\"https://coinmarketcap.com/academy/glossary/ai-agents\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\">AI agent</a> assistant created by developer Peter Steinberger. Unlike a standard chatbot, OpenClaw is designed to live on your local hardware — often a Mac Mini — and execute real-world tasks.</p><p>It can:</p><ul><li>Control your browser</li><li>Run terminal commands</li><li>Plan and execute tasks autonomously</li><li>Communicate with you via WhatsApp or Telegram.</li></ul><p>Its \"local-first\" architecture means your private data never leaves your server, a feature that has made it popular among privacy-conscious crypto natives.</p><p>It launched publicly in November 2025, but didn’t gain widespread attention until December 2025 following the success of Anthropic’s Claude Code.</p><p>OpenClaw has since gone viral, <a href=\"https://github.com/moltbot/moltbot\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\">recording</a> over 100,000 stars on <a href=\"https://coinmarketcap.com/academy/glossary/github\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\">GitHub</a> (similar to Instagram likes) and securing mentions in high-profile publications including <a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/ronschmelzer/2026/01/27/viral-ai-sidekick-clawdbot-changes-name-to-moltbot-and-sheds-its-old-skin/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\">Forbes</a> and <a href=\"https://www.wired.com/story/clawdbot-moltbot-viral-ai-assistant/\" rel=\"no"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":5500,"aggregated":"found 1\nPATH root.props.pageProps.article\nkeys dict_keys(['id', 'title', 'slug', 'meta', 'visible', 'image', 'content', 'disclaimer', 'language', 'created_at', 'updated_at', 'reading_time', 'likes', 'shares', 'srd', 'related', 'available_languages', 'difficulty', 'categories', 'author', 'assets'])\ntitle What is OpenClaw? The AI Agent Assistant Lighting Up Crypto Twitter\ncontent snippet <p>In the fast-moving world of artificial intelligence, a week is a long time. For OpenClaw (formerly Clawdbot and then MoltBot), the last seven days have been a masterclass in viral growth, but trademark disputes and a stream of mishaps have marred its potential.</p><p>What started as a niche tool for developers has turned into a cautionary tale of \"The Great Molt\" — a rebrand that saw millions of dollars vanish in minutes while simultaneously cementing OpenClaw as a potential game-changer for crypto degens.</p><h2 id=\"what-is-openclaw\">What is OpenClaw?</h2><p>OpenClaw is a self-hosted <a href=\"https://coinmarketcap.com/academy/glossary/ai-agents\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\">AI agent</a> assistant created by developer Peter Steinberger. Unlike a standard chatbot, OpenClaw is designed to live on your local hardware — often a Mac Mini — and execute real-world tasks.</p><p>It can:</p><ul><li>Control your browser</li><li>Run terminal commands</li><li>Plan and execute tasks autonomously</li><li>Communicate with you via WhatsApp or Telegram.</li></ul><p>Its \"local-first\" architecture means your private data never leaves your server, a feature that has made it popular among privacy-conscious crypto natives.</p><p>It launched publicly in November 2025, but didn’t gain widespread attention until December 2025 following the success of Anthropic’s Claude Code.</p><p>OpenClaw has since gone viral, <a href=\"https://github.com/moltbot/moltbot\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\">recording</a> over 100,000 stars on <a href=\"https://coinmarketcap.com/academy/glossary/github\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\">GitHub</a> (similar to Instagram likes) and securing mentions in high-profile publications including <a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/ronschmelzer/2026/01/27/viral-ai-sidekick-clawdbot-changes-name-to-moltbot-and-sheds-its-old-skin/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\">Forbes</a> and <a href=\"https://www.wired.com/story/clawdbot-moltbot-viral-ai-assistant/\" rel=\"no","cwd":"/home/zbb/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773892920779}}
{"type":"message","id":"61ff000c","parentId":"1adc8e68","timestamp":"2026-03-19T04:02:10.192Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_LBISNCHhViPVvGSWk21sYKxY","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 - <<'PY'\nimport requests,re,json,html\nfrom html.parser import HTMLParser\n\nclass Strip(HTMLParser):\n    def __init__(self):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.out=[]\n    def handle_starttag(self, tag, attrs):\n        if tag in ('p','h1','h2','h3','li'):\n            self.out.append('\\n')\n        if tag=='li':\n            self.out.append('- ')\n    def handle_data(self, data):\n        self.out.append(data)\n    def get(self):\n        text=''.join(self.out)\n        text=re.sub(r'\\n{3,}','\\n\\n',text)\n        return html.unescape(text).strip()\n\nurl='https://coinmarketcap.com/academy/article/what-is-openclaw-moltbot-clawdbot-ai-agent-crypto-twitter'\ntext=requests.get(url,timeout=20,headers={'User-Agent':'Mozilla/5.0'}).text\nm=re.search(r'<script id=\"__NEXT_DATA__\" type=\"application/json\">(.*?)</script>', text)\ndata=json.loads(html.unescape(m.group(1)))\narticle=data['props']['pageProps']['article']\nparser=Strip(); parser.feed(article['content'])\nprint('TITLE:',article['title'])\nprint('UPDATED:',article['updated_at'])\nprint('AUTHOR:',article['author'])\nprint('\\nTEXT:\\n')\nprint(parser.get())\nPY","workdir":"/home/zbb/.openclaw/workspace","yieldMs":20000,"timeout":40}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":1931,"output":379,"cacheRead":33280,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":35590,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773892920785}}
{"type":"message","id":"01ed56d3","parentId":"61ff000c","timestamp":"2026-03-19T04:02:15.730Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_LBISNCHhViPVvGSWk21sYKxY","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"TITLE: What is OpenClaw? The AI Agent Assistant Lighting Up Crypto Twitter\nUPDATED: 2026-02-09T21:48:58.357Z\nAUTHOR: {'name': 'Daniel Phillips', 'bio_summary': 'Cryptocurrencies are all I talk about. Most of the time. ', 'slug': 'daniel-phillips', 'image': {'original': 'uploads/5157fb7b2c7e44a89e27e6659d02d7d6.jpeg', 'optimized': 'optimized-uploads/5157fb7b2c7e44a89e27e6659d02d7d6.jpeg', 'thumbnail': 'thumbnail-uploads/5157fb7b2c7e44a89e27e6659d02d7d6.jpeg'}}\n\nTEXT:\n\nIn the fast-moving world of artificial intelligence, a week is a long time. For OpenClaw (formerly Clawdbot and then MoltBot), the last seven days have been a masterclass in viral growth, but trademark disputes and a stream of mishaps have marred its potential.\nWhat started as a niche tool for developers has turned into a cautionary tale of \"The Great Molt\" — a rebrand that saw millions of dollars vanish in minutes while simultaneously cementing OpenClaw as a potential game-changer for crypto degens.\nWhat is OpenClaw?\nOpenClaw is a self-hosted AI agent assistant created by developer Peter Steinberger. Unlike a standard chatbot, OpenClaw is designed to live on your local hardware — often a Mac Mini — and execute real-world tasks.\nIt can:\n- Control your browser\n- Run terminal commands\n- Plan and execute tasks autonomously\n- Communicate with you via WhatsApp or Telegram.\nIts \"local-first\" architecture means your private data never leaves your server, a feature that has made it popular among privacy-conscious crypto natives.\nIt launched publicly in November 2025, but didn’t gain widespread attention until December 2025 following the success of Anthropic’s Claude Code.\nOpenClaw has since gone viral, recording over 100,000 stars on GitHub (similar to Instagram likes) and securing mentions in high-profile publications including Forbes and WIRED — making it one of the most visible open-source agent tools right now.\nThe “Molt”\nOpenClaw’s rise to glory wasn’t without hiccups. The project was originally named Clawdbot, but it received a trademark request from AI development firm Anthropic due to its similarity to their \"Claude\" large language model.\nThe team pivoted to the name MoltBot — a metaphor for a lobster shedding its shell to grow.\nBut the transition became a disaster when the team attempted to swap their social media handles.\nIn the few seconds between dropping the old @clawdbot handle and claiming the new one, professional \"handle snipers\" snagged it.\nSource: Peter Steinberger\nThe fallout was immediate and devastating. Scammers used the hijacked X account to launch a fake CLAWD token on Solana. It rocketed to a $16 million market cap within hours but plummeted to near-zero when Steinberger publicly clarified that he had nothing to do with it.\nOn Jan. 29, Steinberger announced that the project would once again change its name, this time to OpenClaw, representing both its open-source nature and lobster heritage.\nThere have been other issues as well. Experts quickly identified that many users were running OpenClaw with exposed API keys and open server ports, effectively leaving the \"master keys\" to their digital lives reachable by any hacker with an IP scanner.\nPlus, there are mounting reports that Anthropic is actively banning users powering their OpenClaw with their Claude credentials, seemingly for violating a clause in its Terms of Service that says its services cannot be used to develop or train any AI or machine learning algorithms or models.\nCrypto Use Cases for OpenClaw\nDespite the user security issues and rough start, the crypto community has embraced OpenClaw for what many say is an unparalleled ability to act as an autonomous on-chain agent.\nHere are some of the most ambitious use cases users have come up with so far.\nPolymarket Yield Sniper\nPrediction markets like Polymarket move at the speed of news. Users are now using OpenClaw to monitor global news feeds and social media sentiment in real time to automate their \"Yes/No\" positions.\nUsing this execution loop, Polymarket traders can reduce the lag that usually costs them the best entry. The practical result is less “human delay” and more opportunities to extract gains from mispricings, an advantage normally reserved for teams running institutional-grade bots.\nSource: Movez\nAutonomous Researcher/Trader\nTraditional research can be a slog, involving hours of scrolling through white papers and reports, aggregating on-chain data, and writing up briefs. OpenClaw users are now creating \"research agents\" that aggregate data into an easy-to-read format for quick decision-making. The result gives traders quicker reads on whether a token is real, liquid, and/or worth deeper attention.\nOthers have gone one step further, giving their OpenClaw live access to a funded crypto wallet and directing it to trade automatically using its insights.\nSource: Legendary\nThat said, it’s important to separate the hype from the reality here. Most positive results are unsubstantiated, but the proof of concept is there.\nDon’t have time to get to grips with OpenClaw? Give CMC AI a try.\nPassive \"Airdrop Farming\" at Scale\nAirdrop farming can be incredibly tedious and repetitive, especially when taken to extremes.\nFarmers are using OpenClaw to automate \"proof of activity\" across dozens of testnets, allowing them to automatically perform daily tasks like bridging small amounts of Ethereum (ETH), swapping on a decentralized exchange (DEX), or interacting with Discord channels to maintain \"active\" status.\nSource: Yield Prime\nBecause OpenClaw runs locally, it can maintain persistent sessions across multiple browser profiles without triggering \"bot detection\" as easily as cloud-based scripts. Some people are already using this to bypass the typical Sybil defenses used by many airdrop campaigns.\nThe result is greater consistency and less manual effort, turning a tedious grind into a systematic workflow — albeit at the expense of projects seeking genuine user engagement.\nOn-Chain Sentry\nAnother unique OpenClaw crypto workflow is running it as a 24/7 market sentinel.\nCreative users are utilizing it to track whale wallets and monitor big exchange inflows/outflows, liquidation spikes, and open interest changes, as well as sudden narrative shifts. It can then ping them on Telegram/Discord the moment something interesting happens.\nSource: Mugi\nInstead of manually refreshing dashboards, the bot uses loops to automatically scan, detect, , giving you an edge over those still doing it the “old-fashioned way.”\nCrypto and the Agentic Economy\nIf the agentic economy takes off, what will agents use to transact?\nAn AI agent can’t walk into a bank, pass Know Your Customer (KYC) checks, or tap “approve” in your banking app, but it can hold a crypto wallet and settle payments autonomously using digital assets.\nThis lack of friction makes crypto a natural rail for AI agents to buy data, compute, and services without human bottlenecks. Still, autonomy raises big questions around trust, safety, and accountability.\nAs agents start “doing business” for us, will crypto become their default payment layer? So far, the case is compelling.\nFurther reading: 5 Ways AI Agents May Actually Make Your Life Easier in 2026"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":5530,"aggregated":"TITLE: What is OpenClaw? The AI Agent Assistant Lighting Up Crypto Twitter\nUPDATED: 2026-02-09T21:48:58.357Z\nAUTHOR: {'name': 'Daniel Phillips', 'bio_summary': 'Cryptocurrencies are all I talk about. Most of the time. ', 'slug': 'daniel-phillips', 'image': {'original': 'uploads/5157fb7b2c7e44a89e27e6659d02d7d6.jpeg', 'optimized': 'optimized-uploads/5157fb7b2c7e44a89e27e6659d02d7d6.jpeg', 'thumbnail': 'thumbnail-uploads/5157fb7b2c7e44a89e27e6659d02d7d6.jpeg'}}\n\nTEXT:\n\nIn the fast-moving world of artificial intelligence, a week is a long time. For OpenClaw (formerly Clawdbot and then MoltBot), the last seven days have been a masterclass in viral growth, but trademark disputes and a stream of mishaps have marred its potential.\nWhat started as a niche tool for developers has turned into a cautionary tale of \"The Great Molt\" — a rebrand that saw millions of dollars vanish in minutes while simultaneously cementing OpenClaw as a potential game-changer for crypto degens.\nWhat is OpenClaw?\nOpenClaw is a self-hosted AI agent assistant created by developer Peter Steinberger. Unlike a standard chatbot, OpenClaw is designed to live on your local hardware — often a Mac Mini — and execute real-world tasks.\nIt can:\n- Control your browser\n- Run terminal commands\n- Plan and execute tasks autonomously\n- Communicate with you via WhatsApp or Telegram.\nIts \"local-first\" architecture means your private data never leaves your server, a feature that has made it popular among privacy-conscious crypto natives.\nIt launched publicly in November 2025, but didn’t gain widespread attention until December 2025 following the success of Anthropic’s Claude Code.\nOpenClaw has since gone viral, recording over 100,000 stars on GitHub (similar to Instagram likes) and securing mentions in high-profile publications including Forbes and WIRED — making it one of the most visible open-source agent tools right now.\nThe “Molt”\nOpenClaw’s rise to glory wasn’t without hiccups. The project was originally named Clawdbot, but it received a trademark request from AI development firm Anthropic due to its similarity to their \"Claude\" large language model.\nThe team pivoted to the name MoltBot — a metaphor for a lobster shedding its shell to grow.\nBut the transition became a disaster when the team attempted to swap their social media handles.\nIn the few seconds between dropping the old @clawdbot handle and claiming the new one, professional \"handle snipers\" snagged it.\nSource: Peter Steinberger\nThe fallout was immediate and devastating. Scammers used the hijacked X account to launch a fake CLAWD token on Solana. It rocketed to a $16 million market cap within hours but plummeted to near-zero when Steinberger publicly clarified that he had nothing to do with it.\nOn Jan. 29, Steinberger announced that the project would once again change its name, this time to OpenClaw, representing both its open-source nature and lobster heritage.\nThere have been other issues as well. Experts quickly identified that many users were running OpenClaw with exposed API keys and open server ports, effectively leaving the \"master keys\" to their digital lives reachable by any hacker with an IP scanner.\nPlus, there are mounting reports that Anthropic is actively banning users powering their OpenClaw with their Claude credentials, seemingly for violating a clause in its Terms of Service that says its services cannot be used to develop or train any AI or machine learning algorithms or models.\nCrypto Use Cases for OpenClaw\nDespite the user security issues and rough start, the crypto community has embraced OpenClaw for what many say is an unparalleled ability to act as an autonomous on-chain agent.\nHere are some of the most ambitious use cases users have come up with so far.\nPolymarket Yield Sniper\nPrediction markets like Polymarket move at the speed of news. Users are now using OpenClaw to monitor global news feeds and social media sentiment in real time to automate their \"Yes/No\" positions.\nUsing this execution loop, Polymarket traders can reduce the lag that usually costs them the best entry. The practical result is less “human delay” and more opportunities to extract gains from mispricings, an advantage normally reserved for teams running institutional-grade bots.\nSource: Movez\nAutonomous Researcher/Trader\nTraditional research can be a slog, involving hours of scrolling through white papers and reports, aggregating on-chain data, and writing up briefs. OpenClaw users are now creating \"research agents\" that aggregate data into an easy-to-read format for quick decision-making. The result gives traders quicker reads on whether a token is real, liquid, and/or worth deeper attention.\nOthers have gone one step further, giving their OpenClaw live access to a funded crypto wallet and directing it to trade automatically using its insights.\nSource: Legendary\nThat said, it’s important to separate the hype from the reality here. Most positive results are unsubstantiated, but the proof of concept is there.\nDon’t have time to get to grips with OpenClaw? Give CMC AI a try.\nPassive \"Airdrop Farming\" at Scale\nAirdrop farming can be incredibly tedious and repetitive, especially when taken to extremes.\nFarmers are using OpenClaw to automate \"proof of activity\" across dozens of testnets, allowing them to automatically perform daily tasks like bridging small amounts of Ethereum (ETH), swapping on a decentralized exchange (DEX), or interacting with Discord channels to maintain \"active\" status.\nSource: Yield Prime\nBecause OpenClaw runs locally, it can maintain persistent sessions across multiple browser profiles without triggering \"bot detection\" as easily as cloud-based scripts. Some people are already using this to bypass the typical Sybil defenses used by many airdrop campaigns.\nThe result is greater consistency and less manual effort, turning a tedious grind into a systematic workflow — albeit at the expense of projects seeking genuine user engagement.\nOn-Chain Sentry\nAnother unique OpenClaw crypto workflow is running it as a 24/7 market sentinel.\nCreative users are utilizing it to track whale wallets and monitor big exchange inflows/outflows, liquidation spikes, and open interest changes, as well as sudden narrative shifts. It can then ping them on Telegram/Discord the moment something interesting happens.\nSource: Mugi\nInstead of manually refreshing dashboards, the bot uses loops to automatically scan, detect, , giving you an edge over those still doing it the “old-fashioned way.”\nCrypto and the Agentic Economy\nIf the agentic economy takes off, what will agents use to transact?\nAn AI agent can’t walk into a bank, pass Know Your Customer (KYC) checks, or tap “approve” in your banking app, but it can hold a crypto wallet and settle payments autonomously using digital assets.\nThis lack of friction makes crypto a natural rail for AI agents to buy data, compute, and services without human bottlenecks. Still, autonomy raises big questions around trust, safety, and accountability.\nAs agents start “doing business” for us, will crypto become their default payment layer? So far, the case is compelling.\nFurther reading: 5 Ways AI Agents May Actually Make Your Life Easier in 2026","cwd":"/home/zbb/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773892935727}}
{"type":"message","id":"bfe57c41","parentId":"01ed56d3","timestamp":"2026-03-19T04:03:37.137Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"这篇 CoinMarketCap Academy 的文章，核心是在讲：**OpenClaw 是什么、为什么突然在加密圈爆火，以及它在爆火过程中踩过哪些坑。**\n\n先说结论版：  \n**OpenClaw 是一个本地部署、可执行真实操作的 AI Agent 助手。** 它不是普通聊天机器人，而是能直接帮你“动手做事”的那种：能控制浏览器、跑终端命令、规划并执行任务，还能通过 WhatsApp 或 Telegram 跟你沟通。文章强调它的一个卖点是 **local-first**，也就是尽量跑在你自己的机器上（文中举例是 Mac Mini），因此私密数据不必上传到别人服务器。这一点很对加密圈那种既想自动化、又非常敏感隐私和主权的人胃口。\n\n它之所以火，文章给了两个层面的原因。  \n第一层是产品层面：**它提供了一种“真正能行动”的 AI 助手形态**，不是只会答题，而是能替你去看网页、执行流程、盯市场、甚至在某些设定下直接连钱包做链上动作。  \n第二层是传播层面：**它踩中了 AI Agent + Crypto Twitter 这两个最会制造情绪和叙事的圈子**。文章说它 2025 年 11 月公开发布，但真正大范围出圈是在 12 月、尤其是在 Anthropic 的 Claude Code 走红之后。随后它的 GitHub 星标冲到 10 万+，还被 Forbes、WIRED 之类媒体提到，于是从“开发者小圈子工具”变成了“所有加密玩家都在讨论的现象级项目”。\n\n这篇文章里最有戏剧性的部分，是它的**命名演化史**。  \n一开始项目叫 **Clawdbot**。后来因为这个名字和 Anthropic 的 Claude 过于接近，团队收到了商标相关要求，于是改名成 **MoltBot**。“molt” 是甲壳类蜕壳的意思，算是个挺贴切的龙虾梗。  \n但真正的事故就出在这次改名上：团队在切换社交媒体账号时，短暂释放了旧账号名，结果被专门抢用户名的人瞬间抢走。随后骗子利用被劫持的 X 账号，发了一个假的 **CLAWD** Solana 代币，市值短时间冲到 1600 万美元左右，之后在作者本人澄清“这不是我发的”之后几乎归零。  \n再后来，1 月 29 日项目又一次改名，变成 **OpenClaw**。这个名字一方面突出开源属性，另一方面也保留了“claw/龙虾钳”的意象。文章其实把这一整段包装成了一个很典型的 crypto drama：**一次品牌重命名，瞬间引发投机、诈骗、踩踏和更大范围传播**。你可以理解成，项目真正“封神”的一部分原因，恰恰不是它多平稳，而是它够混乱、够有戏。\n\n文章对 OpenClaw 的主要判断，大概有几条：\n\n第一，**它可能是当前最有代表性的开源 AI Agent 工具之一**。  \n这是作者想传达的主线。不是说它已经成熟无敌，而是说它把“AI 真正代替用户执行操作”这件事，做到了足够可见、足够能引发模仿。\n\n第二，**它对加密用户尤其有吸引力，因为加密世界天然适合 agent 自动化。**  \n文章后半段几乎全在往这个方向拉：如果未来真有“agentic economy（代理人经济）”，AI agent 要自己收付款、买数据、买算力、调用服务，传统银行体系并不适合，因为 agent 没法过 KYC、没法人工点审批；但 crypto wallet 却天然适合机器持有和调用。所以作者的潜台词是：**AI agent 的执行层 + 加密货币的支付结算层，可能是天生一对。**\n\n第三，**它现在的厉害之处更多还是“概念验证”与“工作流创新”，不是已经大规模验证过的稳定赚钱机器。**  \n这点文章倒没有完全失真，它明确提了一句：很多所谓“正收益案例”其实缺乏扎实证据，更多还是 hype 先行，但至少 proof of concept 已经有了。也就是：能跑通，不等于稳赚。\n\n文中举了几个加密场景下的典型用法：\n\n- **Polymarket 预测市场自动化**：实时盯新闻、社交媒体情绪，然后自动调整 Yes/No 仓位，减少人类反应延迟。  \n- **自主研究员 / 交易员**：自动汇总白皮书、链上数据、项目资料，做成摘要，有些人甚至进一步让它接入真钱包自动交易。  \n- **大规模空投 farming**：在多个测试网、多个浏览器 profile 里自动完成日常交互，比如桥接、swap、Discord 活跃等。  \n- **24/7 链上哨兵**：持续盯巨鲸地址、交易所流入流出、清算、未平仓量、叙事变化，然后在 Telegram/Discord 里提醒你。\n\n这些案例里，文章最看重的是一种优势：**OpenClaw 跑在本地，所以能保持持久会话、多 profile 操作，而且不那么容易像云端脚本那样一下子被认成 bot。** 对很多空投党和量化味很重的 crypto 用户来说，这个想象空间非常大。\n\n但文章也不是纯吹，它提到的**风险和争议**其实不少：\n\n1. **安全风险很大。**  \n   很多人把 OpenClaw 跑起来时，暴露了 API key 和服务器端口，等于把自己数字生活的总钥匙直接挂在公网。文章这点说得挺重，本质上是在提醒：一个能帮你“操作一切”的 agent，如果部署习惯很差，那就是一个超高权限攻击面。\n\n2. **和 Anthropic 的关系并不稳定。**  \n   文中提到，越来越多用户反馈：如果你是拿 Claude 凭据去驱动 OpenClaw，可能会被 Anthropic 封号，因为这可能违反其服务条款中关于不得用于开发/训练 AI 或机器学习系统的相关限制。  \n   这一点的含义是：**OpenClaw 本身是开源的，但你依赖的上层模型服务未必欢迎这种玩法。**\n\n3. **加密应用里有明显灰区，甚至直接带点黑。**  \n   比如文章写空投 farming 时，直接承认一些人是在借它绕过项目方的 Sybil 防御。这其实已经不是“提高效率”那么简单，而是站到了“薅项目方”的一边。文章没有严厉谴责，但也点出这会损害项目想要的真实用户参与。\n\n4. **市场 hype 和诈骗共生。**  \n   从被抢号到假币暴拉暴跌，这篇文章其实在暗示：只要一个 AI/crypto 项目叙事够热，围绕它的骗局就会长得非常快。\n\n如果说这篇文章有什么**明显的 framing / 叙事偏向**，我觉得主要有三点：\n\n- **它明显是站在“这东西很酷、很有未来”的角度写的。**  \n  虽然写了风险，但整体基调还是“有点乱、有点危险、但非常值得关注”。它不是冷静的技术评测，更像一篇带强烈市场叙事感的趋势文章。\n\n- **它在刻意把 OpenClaw 往“AI agent 与 crypto 融合的代表样本”上抬。**  \n  换句话说，这篇文并不只是介绍一个工具，而是在借 OpenClaw 证明一个更大的命题：**AI agent 经济如果成立，加密货币会是它的自然基础设施。**\n\n- **它的案例选择天然偏向加密圈最容易让人兴奋的用法。**  \n  像自动研究、盯盘、空投批量 farming、链上哨兵，这些都很能刺激“效率暴涨、先手优势、自动赚钱”的想象。文章虽然有一句“很多正面结果并未证实”，但整体仍然是在放大这种想象力。\n\n如果用更直白的话概括这篇文章：  \n它把 OpenClaw 写成了一个**介于“真有东西的开源 AI agent”与“被 crypto 圈情绪放大后的热门叙事载体”之间的项目**。  \n它的确有产品力：本地部署、可执行真实任务、适合高隐私和高自动化需求。  \n它也确实很会制造话题：改名风波、抢号事故、假币闹剧、平台封禁、安全翻车，一个不落。  \n所以它爆火，既是因为它有用，也是因为它足够像这个时代的互联网产品——**强、野、乱、能干活，也能惹事。**"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":4764,"output":2139,"cacheRead":31104,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":38007,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773892935732}}
